  <!-- 15. Description -->
  <descriptions>
    <description xml:lang="en" descriptionType="Abstract">
      The Iris dataset is one of the most well-known datasets in the pattern recognition
      literature, first introduced by British statistician and biologist Ronald A. Fisher
      in his 1936 paper "The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems." It
      contains 150 observations of iris flowers across three species (Iris setosa,
      Iris virginica, and Iris versicolor), with four morphological features recorded
      for each sample: sepal length, sepal width, petal length, and petal width, all
      measured in centimetres. The dataset is widely used for testing classification
      algorithms and exploratory data analysis in machine learning and statistics.
    </description>
    <description xml:lang="en" descriptionType="Methods">
      Measurements were collected by Edgar Anderson at the Gaspé Peninsula, Canada.
      Each of the three iris species is represented by 50 samples. Measurements
      include sepal length (cm), sepal width (cm), petal length (cm), and petal
      width (cm).
    </description>
    <description xml:lang="en" descriptionType="TechnicalInfo">
      Format: CSV | Rows: 150 | Columns: 5 (sepal_length, sepal_width, petal_length,
      petal_width, species) | Missing values: None | Classes: 3
      (Iris-setosa, Iris-versicolor, Iris-virginica)
    </description>
  </descriptions>

